Silloin minulle 2.5kWh l√§mp√∂√§ maksaa dieselill√§ 48c tai sitten maal√§mm√∂ll√§ saman jos s√§hk√∂ maksaa 42c   siirtohinta 6c. Muuten perusl√§mp√∂ kannattaa pit√§√§ maal√§mp√∂n√§. Puhallin kuluttaa s√§hk√∂√§ mutta s√§hk√∂nkulutus on todella pient√§ l√§mp√∂tehoon n√§hden joten j√§tin sen laskelmasta yksinkertaistuksena pois.

Kannattavuutta laskiessa pit√§√§ ensiksi laskea miten paljon dieselill√§ l√§mmitt√§minen maksaa. Sen saa laskemalla "tuntikulutus x litrahinta" / "tunnin l√§mp√∂tuotto". Minulla t√§m√§ luku on 0.19 euroa eli 19 centti√§ per kilowattitunti. 

Erilaisilla pumpuilla saa saa yhdell√§ kilowatttunnilla s√§hk√∂√§ enemm√§n energiaa kuin mit√§ energian tuottaminen kuluttaa s√§hk√∂√§. Laske ensiksi "menetelm√§si hy√∂tysuhde x diesell√§mmityksen hinta" niin tied√§t miten paljon dieselill√§ maksaa tuottaa saman verran energiaa kuin yhdell√§ kilowattitunnilla  s√§hk√∂√§. S√§hk√∂√∂n tulee 0.06e eli 6c siirtokustannusta joten s√§hk√∂n arvonlis√§verollinen hinta pit√§√§ olla 6c halvempi kuin laskeman tulos. 

Mit√§ korkeampi hy√∂tysuhde - sit√§ kalliimpaa s√§hk√∂√§ kannattaa k√§ytt√§√§. Minulla on ajatuksena k√§ytt√§√§ l√§mmitint√§ nostamaan hallinl√§mp√∂tilaa kovilla pakkasilla s√§hk√∂nhinnan ollessa todella taivaassa ja s√§hk√∂n uhatessa loppua Suomesta. recommandationVideos.Title: India's Infra Thrust To Ladakh: Countering China & Pakistan
recommandationVideos.Description:
India‚Äôs military is in the fourth winter of its advanced forward deployment against China‚Äôs People‚Äôs Liberation Army (PLA) forces along the Line of Actual Control (LAC) in eastern Ladakh. China‚Äôs renewed aggression in 2020 led to the deadly Galwan clashes in June that year, with the consequent military buildup and standoff. Both sides continue to engage at the military, diplomatic and political level. But the shattering of trust, protocols and agreements means India is on perpetual guard in the present while ramping up its preparedness for the future.

StratNews Global‚Äôs team of Amitabh P. Revi, Rohit Pandita and Karan Marwaha travels along alpine altitudes through the frozen desert landscape in eastern Ladakh and Siachen to bring you this series: The Himalayan Frontier. These ground reports document the sustained infrastructure push in road connectivity and air bridges, record substantial progress in alternate axes that are in play and are being planned, and capture on camera how the Indian Army, the Border Roads Organisation (BRO) and the Indian Air Force‚Äôs women, men and machines are honing their all-weather readiness during another winter, against the two-front threat from China and Pakistan.

In this episode, we travel from Manali, through the Atal Tunnel under the Rohtang Pass and drive on the Darcha-Padam-Nimmu (NPD) road to Leh. This is a crucial third axis to Leh that will ensure all-weather connectivity for India's military and civilians, even when upto fifteen foot high snow walls usually close passes as high as 17,000  feet for months in the winter. The Border Roads Organisation (BRO) is the nodal agency for this infrastructural push and we travel with their personnel to understand their engineering achievements through bone-chilling alpine altitudes, how they drill through mountain ranges, lay bridges across fast-moving rivers and the challenges at these heights, temperatures and topographies.
